<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-589-917  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 589 917.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC World  Dec 1990 v8 n12 p202(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>On site: putting Windows to work.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>LaPlante, Alice.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>How smooth the transition will be from character-based computingto a graphical environment such as Microsoft Windows depends onhow quickly users switch over and what kind of hardware they areusing.andP;  At a San Carlos, California municipal office, expenses inthe switch to Windows include the adding of memory chips tosystems that only have 1Mbyte of memory and upgrades for the ROMBIOS on several machines that is incompatible with Windows 3.0.andP;  Abiotech research firm in Redwood City, California, runs Windowssuccessfully on its 286 machines since employees have little needfor multitasking.andP;  However, any future microcomputer buying willinvolve 386SX machines.andP;  A large New York bank uses Windows on 486systems to provide users with a consistent interface among allapplications, to allow them to multitask and to let them sharedata among applications by way of Windows' DDE capability.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   Microsoft Windows (Graphical user interface) (Usage).andO;Topic:     User NeedsSoftware MigrationGraphical User InterfaceUser Interface.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>